@Arkangel2

As Caitlin explained in her column,

‘18A. This is a hidden-word clue, the kind you’d find in a cryptic or puns-and-anagrams puzzle. The [Woman in dire need?] in this case is RENEE, composed of consecutive letters in “dire need.”’

@Adina 

Crosswords are ALL trivia!

It's not like there's a cancer cure or a Grand Unified Theory in any of them.

@Daryl 

Of all the "rules" that I've heard about crosswords, the idea that a word can't appear both as an answer and in a clue is the strangest one of all.

Where are people getting these "rules"?

@D Bean 

A proper cryptic clue has to be unambiguous because not every letter crosses. This clue is not a proper cryptic clue but has a likeness to one. 



!!!!

@Weinie I’ll never understand complaints about the presence of some amount of deliberately obscure trivia and/or vocab in a puzzle, especially later in the week.

TBH I actually have no idea how obscure that particular entry is for the wider group, but I’ve personally never heard of Courtney Barnett or Kurt Vile, so it was totally opaque to me. As were SAMARA Weaving, LAALAA, and  ELIZA. But why stop there? Plenty of people have probably never heard of the Philly Phanatic, and I’m sure a non-trivial cohort of solvers won’t immediately associate FINCH with To Kill a Mockingbird. I had also never heard the expression “so extra”.

But you’re going to call this an awful puzzle because you haven’t heard of a music group in one of the clues and because LATS aren’t the primary muscle exercised in rows?

@CCNY 

Well, for one thing, it didn’t have a theme. 

I did the puzzle in a car with someone who occasionally was making conversation, so neither my time nor my experience is an indication of how hard it was.

