@Bruce 

Ah, ok, thanks. I knew this meaning of "ditch" but have never heard of ditch day.

In Polish school in the 1980s and 90s we used to have a ditch day on the 1st day of spring, 21st March. We called it "dzień wagarowicza" ("wagary" is a Polish term for skipping school, and "wagarowicz" is somebody who engages in wagary; "dzień" means day), and it was the only time during the whole year that we were not penalized for skipping school. A quick web search reveals that Dzień wagarowicza is still a thing.

@Bruce

Love "like the Phoenix rising"!

Ever since I stopped playing for speed, I wait for crosses before filling in words that aren't locks, and love finding out that my first guess was correct.

@Anil 

As Steve L observed in a different thread about RENEE, a clue like that would more likely be unambiguous in a British-style cryptic because when so few letters are checked by crossing words, ambiguity is a bigger challenge. 

There are clues with two or more possible answers in puzzles all the time. That’s all this was.

